<BlogLayout frontmatter={frontmatter}>
  <p class="text-xl text-silver leading-relaxed mb-8">
    Most "mining" burns energy to solve useless puzzles. Silica flips that—every joule of compute contributes to real science.
  </p>

  <h2>The Problem with Traditional Mining</h2>
  <p>
    Bitcoin's proof of work is brilliant cryptography but terrible resource allocation:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Wasted compute:</strong> Trillions of hashes computed and immediately discarded</li>
    <li><strong>Energy consumption:</strong> More electricity than many countries</li>
    <li><strong>No useful output:</strong> The only product is network security</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    What if that compute did something valuable?
  </p>

  <h2>Proof of Useful Work (PoUW)</h2>
  <p>
    Silica miners contribute to real distributed computing projects:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>BOINC integration:</strong> Scientific computing projects (protein folding, climate modeling, etc.)</li>
    <li><strong>AI/ML training:</strong> Model training and inference tasks</li>
    <li><strong>Data analytics:</strong> Large-scale data processing jobs</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="tech-details">
    <h3>Work Submission Flow</h3>
    <pre><code>async fn execute_useful_work(&amp;mut self) -&gt; Result&lt;WorkResult&gt;;
async fn submit_work_proof(&amp;self, work: WorkResult) -&gt; Result&lt;ProofSubmission&gt;;</code></pre>
    <p>Nodes submit Merkle proofs of completed tasks, which are verified and anchored into lineations (periodic chain anchors).</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Power-Optimized Network</h2>
  <p>
    Silica is designed so that every joule of energy counts:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Low-resource validators:</strong> Home nodes can participate as Gateways or DAS samplers without datacenter hardware</li>
    <li><strong>Efficient pipeline:</strong> Alluvium + Tephra + Crystallite + Lithification minimizes CPU and bandwidth compared to heavy PoW systems</li>
    <li><strong>Dual-purpose energy:</strong> Security and computation happen together, not in competition</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Incentive Balance</h2>
  <p>
    To keep the system fair and efficient:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Project multipliers:</strong> Certain research projects can earn bonus rewards if voted by governance</li>
    <li><strong>Anti-gaming checks:</strong> Verifiers and oracles ensure submitted work is genuine, not fake or recycled</li>
    <li><strong>Scheduler boosts:</strong> Consistent contributors may receive priority and rewards</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="info-box">
    <h3>Comprehensive Verification</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Validator Population Synthesis:</strong> Realistic stake distributions and geographic clustering</li>
      <li><strong>Adversarial Scenario Modeling:</strong> Byzantine fractions, equivocation, withholding attacks</li>
      <li><strong>Validator Selection Validation:</strong> Gini coefficient analysis, proposer fairness metrics</li>
      <li><strong>Geographic Distribution Testing:</strong> H3 cell coverage and sybil resistance validation</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>Why This Matters</h2>

  <div class="benefits-grid">
    <div class="benefit-card">
      <h3>For the Environment</h3>
      <p>No wasted hashing—energy goes to useful computation</p>
    </div>
    <div class="benefit-card">
      <h3>For Society</h3>
      <p>Every node helps advance real science or AI</p>
    </div>
    <div class="benefit-card">
      <h3>For Users</h3>
      <p>Earn rewards knowing your energy matters</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Getting Started</h2>
  <p>
    Running a useful work node is straightforward:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Install the miner:</strong> Download and configure the Chert miner</li>
    <li><strong>Select projects:</strong> Choose which scientific projects to contribute to</li>
    <li><strong>Start earning:</strong> Completed work units translate directly to CHERT rewards</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="cta-section">
    <h2>Mine with Purpose</h2>
    <p>
      Silica proves blockchain doesn't have to be wasteful—it can be a force for progress.
    </p>
